# Backend Security and Authentication

- Validate every external input at the boundary (request body, params, query, headers).
- Never trust client-supplied roles or permissions; derive authz from verified server-side identity.
- Use least privilege for role checks and reject by default when role is missing/unknown.
- Store secrets only in environment variables; never hardcode API keys, tokens, or credentials.
- Hash passwords with a strong adaptive algorithm (bcrypt/argon2); never log plaintext secrets.
- Return generic auth errors to clients and keep sensitive failure details in server logs only.

```ts
// ❌ BAD: trusts client role + weak auth check
if (req.body.role === "admin") {
  return next();
}

// ✅ GOOD: uses verified identity and explicit role check
const userRole = req.user?.role;
if (userRole !== "admin") {
  return res.status(403).json({ message: "Forbidden" });
}
return next();
```

```ts
// ❌ BAD: missing validation
await createUser(req.body);

// ✅ GOOD: validate before use
const parsed = CreateUserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
if (!parsed.success) {
  return res.status(400).json({ message: "Invalid request" });
}
await createUser(parsed.data);
```
